entry.title: [Privacy Sandbox] Do not convert attestation list directory using
entry.content:
AsUTF8Unsafe().



From histograms, we found there is a Windows specific issue that the

std::ifstream fails to open. I tested the existing implementation and

found it fails to open the file when the directory contains combining

characters, for example "ร" and "รถ". See crrev.com/c/5089910 for the

try bot failures.



I realize that the converted directory returned by

`base::FilePath::AsUTF8Unsafe()` is not guaranteed to work across

platforms. We should stick to `base::FilePath`.



Changed to `ReadFileToString`, then `ParseFromString`. It seems most

existing proto parsing implementation in Chromium is done this way.



Although there is no crash reports that we can use to investigate if

the combining character is actually the root cause, this is a fix we

should make.

entry.title: Fix dangling ptr in IndexedDBTestFirstOrThirdParty
entry.content:
A helper object, LevelDBLock, stored a pointer to a leveldb::FileLock

that was returned from a call to LockFile. The pointer represented

ownership of the FileLock and was freed later during a call to

UnlockFile. However, the pointer wasn't being cleared as part of that

call, leading to the dangling pointer warning.



This CL updates LevelDBLock to use std::unique_ptr instead of a raw_ptr

for holding the FileLock pointer. This avoids both the dangling pointer

issue and helps ensure any future use of LevelDBLock will understand

the ownership contract that was previously present, but unstated.

entry.title: Allow separate X/Y values for gaussian blur std-deviation.
entry.content:
The Gaussian blur canvas layer filter previously only supported one

value for the `stdDeviation` attribute. However, the SVG specification

supports anisotropic blurs, with different values for the X and the Y

axis:



https://drafts.fxtf.org/filter-effects/#element-attrdef-fegaussianblur-stddeviation



Canvas filters are defined as following the SVG specification, so

we must support distinct X and Y blur std-deviations.

entry.title: [mullet m3] Call PrepareToFetch when credit card suggestions are shown.
entry.content:
Credit card fetching preflight call needs to be made when we show

masked server credit cards. BAM::DidShowSuggestions checked that

the triggering field type is of credit card group and the

CreditCardAccessManager::PrepareToFetchCreditCards checked that

the user has server credit cards to suggest.



Mullet M3 introduces the flow where the user is able to trigger

credit card suggestions on any form. Now BAM looks at the actual

list of shown suggestions and calls CreditCardAccessManager if

credit card suggestions were shown.

entry.title: [Passwords] Invoke CleanUpFillerAndReportOutcome() when filling
entry.content:
CleanUpFillerAndReportOutcome() has two responsibilities:

1- Report PasswordManager.TouchToFill.Outcome

2- Do the cleanup and deleting the filler.



This is called in all flows where the touch-to-fill UI is dismissed

except after filling credentials.



TouchToFillControllerAutofillDelegate::FillCredential() does report

metrics already, and it seems plausiable that it should also clear the

filler state since the UI is dismissed afterward.



This CL is calling CleanUpFillerAndReportOutcome() also in the

FillCredential() method.



This is necessary since more clean-up will be added in follow-up CLs

and it helps to have it in one place in the code.

entry.title: Remove DCHECK for checking shelf icon click behavior
entry.content:
Three DCHECK were added in crrev.com/c/4688956 as a temporary solution

to address naming confusions from code that goes back to 10 years ago.

As was discussed in b/315364997, the DCHECK failed to address a specific

case when the user first uses tab key to locate the icon, and then uses

the enter key to launch the app.



As not one but quite a few keyboard input combination can be used to

launch an icon on the shelf, such as first tab then enter, or with

ChromeVoX running first tab then space, a DCHECK that specifically

checks certain keycodes is not a viable option. This CL removes all

three DCHECK, while updating the documentation to try to create a most

comprehensive context on the origin of the confusing naming disparity

between key press and key release events.

entry.title: Update TopAlignedImageView to never add letter/pillarbox
entry.content:
Prior to this CL, when a landscape image was displayed, its height

matched the view height, and its width was smaller than the view's

width, ending up with a pillarbox effect (vertical bands on each side of

the image).

With this CL, preparing the way for landscape grid cells, the view is

now favoring matching its width when the image is narrower than the

view, and its height, when the image is wider than the view. This means

that there is never letterbox or pillarbox, i.e. there is always some

clipping. When clipping the width, the image stays centered. When

clipping the height, as the class aludes, the top is preserved and the

bottom is clipped.



But there is an exception because a Tab Grid animation needs a wider

image to fit in width with the viewโฆ So this CL gets a bit more compelx than desired.

entry.title: [//ui] Restrict GpuMemoryBuffer::SetColorSpace() to Apple
entry.content:
This method is implemented only for IOSurface-backed GMBs, where it

calls through to the underlying IOSurface. This CL restricts the method

to being declared only for BUILDFLAG(IS_APPLE), which will facilitate

replacing it with direct calls to set the ColorSpace of the underlying

IOSurface when converting callsites away from using GpuMemoryBuffer in

favor of using GpuMemoryBufferHandle.



Note: When doing those conversions we will need to look at whether we

need to take into account the fact that GMBImplIOSurface caches the

last-set ColorSpace in order to avoid redundant calls on the IOSurface.

The first callsite we will convert (DrawingBuffer) calls SetColorSpace()

immediately after construction of the GMB, so caching is not an issue.

entry.title: [iOS] Ensures test fails gracefully if cookies are not available
entry.content:
When a test suite is executed, it should be able to run each tests,

even the tests that fails. This means that no test should cause the

program to halt, because of CHECK or of invalid memory.



Earl-grey tests do not stop when an assertion fails. This means that

we can not protect CHECK and memory using EG assertions. The test

will fail but the code should either ensure the run ends or allows the

test to go on as much as possible.



The method to retrieve cookies in earl-grey failed with a DCHECK after

an assertion. This CL ensures that the assertion is logged as failing,

but, instead of triggering a DCHECK, the method returns nil.



Since on objective-C any method can be call on nil, this will not

cause the test to crash later.



Fixed: 1510325
